00:04:08.760 --> 00:04:10.410
I work with data in my day job.

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:12.510
I'm one of the partners
and the Creative Director

00:04:12.510 --> 00:04:15.300
at Accurat, a small data
visualization design firm

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:18.149
that we started in Milan,
Italy, which is my home country.

00:04:18.149 --> 00:04:19.890
And now I also
have a small office

00:04:19.890 --> 00:04:21.649
in New York, where I live.

00:04:21.649 --> 00:04:23.520
And yeah, this is
our talented team

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:25.800
of designers, and data
analysts, and developers.

00:04:25.800 --> 00:04:26.850
They say "hi" from Milan.

00:04:26.850 --> 00:04:28.510
And we're missing some
of them in this picture,

00:04:28.510 --> 00:04:29.890
as it was taken a little ago.

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:31.600
But we hardly are
in the same place,

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:34.620
so that's the more complete
pictures that I have.

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:38.850
So every day, I am, and we
are, presented with challenges

00:04:38.850 --> 00:04:41.480
on how to make sense of a
complex system of informations.

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:44.100
And with my team, we
address, we frame them,

00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:46.780
and we solve them through
visual representation.

00:04:46.780 --> 00:04:49.650
So we work with very different
clients, clients in the IT,

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:52.560
even with tech companies
like Google itself,

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:55.350
but also with many
non-profits and organizations

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:57.300
to create tools and
visualizations that

00:04:57.300 --> 00:05:00.930
can make data accessible, both
to their internal and external

00:05:00.930 --> 00:05:01.620
audiences.

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:03.030
And I will give
you a few example

00:05:03.030 --> 00:05:05.770
of the type of challenges that
we are presented with every day

00:05:05.770 --> 00:05:09.630
to give you a sense, from
working with organizations

00:05:09.630 --> 00:05:13.450
such as IBM, re-imagining how
the whole organization uses

00:05:13.450 --> 00:05:16.130
data visualization on
all of their products

00:05:16.130 --> 00:05:19.080
and how they can work with data
effectively on a daily basis.

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:21.810
So design first, a
practical guide on how

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:24.850
to translate numbers into charts
in the very different cases

00:05:24.850 --> 00:05:27.510
they will encounter, but
also designing guidelines

00:05:27.510 --> 00:05:30.510
for the creation of visuals with
data that will look and feel

00:05:30.510 --> 00:05:34.610
like IBM, to collaborating
with the first Italian woman

00:05:34.610 --> 00:05:36.630
astronaut, Samantha
Cristoforetti,

00:05:36.630 --> 00:05:39.810
creating a live web experience
with the data of her mission

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:42.540
during her six month long
expedition to the International

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:43.500
Space Station.

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:45.900
And that was really
exciting indeed,

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:48.330
but where we actually
involve her funds directly

00:05:48.330 --> 00:05:50.460
in the experience,
giving them the chance

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:53.640
to interact with her
as she was in space.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:56.160
And to creating and
building real time tools

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:59.550
for social science researchers
that, through visualization,

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:03.990
can help them monitor
large-scale social experiments.

00:06:03.990 --> 00:06:06.000
But I also do more
experimental work

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.370
and artistic work,
such as art commissions

00:06:08.370 --> 00:06:10.980
or self-initiated
projects, where I mainly

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:15.300
try to explore and adopt a
broader definition of data,

00:06:15.300 --> 00:06:17.940
accepting also the more
subjective intimate

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:21.330
and therefore imperfect aspects
of these information systems

00:06:21.330 --> 00:06:23.100
that we live in.

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:25.320
I talk a lot about what
I called it a humanism.

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:28.260
That is my attempt to define
the focus of my research

00:06:28.260 --> 00:06:30.240
and to understand what
my personal contribution

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:31.980
to the field of data could be.

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:34.050
And where here,
I try to advocate

00:06:34.050 --> 00:06:36.180
that to make data
faithfully representative

00:06:36.180 --> 00:06:39.120
of our human nature, we
need to start designing ways

00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:40.210
to include empathy--

00:06:40.210 --> 00:06:42.180
again, imperfection
and human qualities--

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:45.370
into how we collect,
process, and display data.

00:06:45.370 --> 00:06:48.270
And this is really
what guides my work.

00:06:48.270 --> 00:06:50.760
The project that I'm
probably most known for

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:53.280
is called "Dear Data," a
year-long collaboration

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:55.890
with another information
designer, Stefanie Posavec.

00:06:55.890 --> 00:06:59.310
That was, for me, the
big data hangover cure.

00:06:59.310 --> 00:07:01.980
Stefanie and I only
met twice in our life,

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:04.670
where we decided to run
this very radical experiment

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:07.410
around one main question,
is it possible to get

00:07:07.410 --> 00:07:10.960
to know another human
being through data only?

00:07:10.960 --> 00:07:13.140
So for what we called
"Dear Data," every weekend

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:15.420
for one year, we used
our personal data

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:17.240
to get to know each other.

00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:20.570
Every week and for one year,
we would collect personal data

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:24.120
around weekly shared mundane
topics, from our thoughts

00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:26.730
and ideas, to the interaction
with our partners,

00:07:26.730 --> 00:07:29.810
to the compliments that
we gave and received,

00:07:29.810 --> 00:07:34.680
to our most intimate feelings,
so 52 excuses in form

00:07:34.680 --> 00:07:38.210
of data to investigate and
reveal aspects of ourselves

00:07:38.210 --> 00:07:42.150
in our lives, personal data
that we would then manually

00:07:42.150 --> 00:07:46.440
hand draw on a postcard size
sheet of paper that every week,

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:49.050
we would send from London
to New York where I live,

00:07:49.050 --> 00:07:51.390
and from New York to
London, where she lives.

00:07:51.390 --> 00:07:54.300
And I'm always so jealous
of the red London post box

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:56.010
when I show these
slides, compared

00:07:56.010 --> 00:07:59.540
to the creepy [INAUDIBLE]
in New York and [INAUDIBLE]..

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:02.030
So every Monday
and for one year.

00:08:02.030 --> 00:08:05.209
So the front was always the
data drawing and the back

00:08:05.209 --> 00:08:06.750
of the postcard
contained, of course,

00:08:06.750 --> 00:08:09.100
the address of the other
person, but also the legend,

00:08:09.100 --> 00:08:11.620
how to interpret our drawings.

00:08:11.620 --> 00:08:15.150
And so we started looking
at our days through data,

00:08:15.150 --> 00:08:18.060
but not only quantifying
the numbers of times

00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:20.370
we would perform
a certain actions,

00:08:20.370 --> 00:08:22.500
instead adding
context or details

00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:24.390
about why what was
happening, what

00:08:24.390 --> 00:08:26.850
was the situation
and the feeling,

00:08:26.850 --> 00:08:30.470
realizing really, week after
week, how to put ourself

00:08:30.470 --> 00:08:32.880
in these numbers and how
the context of our very

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:34.799
personal stories,
for the moment,

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:38.580
was as important, if not more,
than the activity we were

00:08:38.580 --> 00:08:40.710
counting, if we wanted
to make this data truly

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:43.549
meaningful and
representative of ourselves.

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:46.410
We've investigated our minds
and our most intimate thoughts

00:08:46.410 --> 00:08:48.900
and fears through data,
sharing with the other person

00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:50.420
all the moments we felt--

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:53.280
anxious, sad,
frustrated, fearful,

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:54.990
and explaining why
through the way

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:57.920
we categorized our
moments of negativity.

00:08:57.920 --> 00:09:01.770
And ultimately, as we say,
we have been using data

00:09:01.770 --> 00:09:04.410
as our unique language,
really as our alphabet,

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:07.470
to discover and communicate
our lives to the other person

00:09:07.470 --> 00:09:09.347
for one year.

00:09:09.347 --> 00:09:11.430
After the project, Stefanie
and I worked on a book

00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:13.290
where we illustrated
all of the lessons

00:09:13.290 --> 00:09:15.000
that we've learned
in life and data.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.250
And "Dear Data" has been
exhibited around the world.

00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:19.850
And then to our incredible
joy and surprise,

00:09:19.850 --> 00:09:21.570
it's found the
most exciting home,

00:09:21.570 --> 00:09:23.122
as the original set
of our cards has

00:09:23.122 --> 00:09:25.080
been acquired as part of
a permanent collection

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:27.150
of the Museum of Modern Art.

00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:30.150
But what excited us
even more is that

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:32.640
what really made us
want to explore further

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:35.610
this idea in our jobs, which is
also what I'm doing with Kaki,

00:09:35.610 --> 00:09:38.010
is that "Dear Data" has
been so well received

00:09:38.010 --> 00:09:40.440
from the public outside
the data community.

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:42.270
We've seen really
thousands of postcards

00:09:42.270 --> 00:09:44.430
made by people who
learned about the project

00:09:44.430 --> 00:09:46.660
and wanted to experiment
on themselves,

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:49.980
and even teachers of any
grade using this format

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:52.550
to teach their students
the world of data.

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:54.390
It has, in a way,
opened the idea

00:09:54.390 --> 00:09:56.880
of data to really a
wider audience that

00:09:56.880 --> 00:09:58.920
made it more
approachable, a tool that

00:09:58.920 --> 00:10:00.630
can be useful for
everyone and not

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:03.300
only for who already
work with data

00:10:03.300 --> 00:10:06.530
or is keen to self-tracking.

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:10.020
And I really ask myself, why did
this project resonate so much

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:11.800
outside the data community?

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:14.010
And I feel it's because
it showed that data is not

00:10:14.010 --> 00:10:16.980
interesting, or boring,
or scary, or big

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:20.340
per se, but it's really a
tool in medium [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:23.430
and a material that is
actually out there for everyone

00:10:23.430 --> 00:10:25.960
to use in many different ways.

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:29.610
And this is what guides
all of my projects,

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:31.660
whether they are purely
artistic projects--

00:10:31.660 --> 00:10:33.660
this is a data visualization
that was up at MoMA

00:10:33.660 --> 00:10:36.450
last fall, closing Paola
Antonelli's last exhibition

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:36.980
"Items--

00:10:36.980 --> 00:10:39.313
is Fashion Modern?"-- I don't
know if you got the chance

00:10:39.313 --> 00:10:41.250
to see the exhibition,
where I didn't have

00:10:41.250 --> 00:10:45.420
any data besides the list
of the 111 items of clothing

00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:49.140
and accessories included in the
show and the research material

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:51.180
put together by the curators.

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:53.430
And this was another
project where activity

00:10:53.430 --> 00:10:57.180
builds my data sets by asking
systematic questions that I

00:10:57.180 --> 00:11:01.440
was reading as I was reading
and studying the taxonomies.

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:03.312
But I'm not going to
talk about my projects

00:11:03.312 --> 00:11:05.520
today, though you can find
all of them on my website.

00:11:05.520 --> 00:11:08.730
I wanted to give you a sense of
my approach to data in general

00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:11.070
before talking about
our collaboration,

00:11:11.070 --> 00:11:14.550
because it's also what
I'm using in our work.

00:11:14.550 --> 00:11:16.710
So Kaki and I started
working together

00:11:16.710 --> 00:11:19.560
when design guru John Mayeda,
who, again, you might know,

00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:24.950
called us to collaborate on the
new brand identity for the 200

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:27.530
years anniversary of a
limited edition for Hennessy,

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:31.470
the cognac brand, where we
designed a visual identity made

00:11:31.470 --> 00:11:33.726
of music and data visualization.

00:11:33.726 --> 00:11:36.642
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:11:43.450 --> 00:11:45.500
And this is, of
course, Kaki playing.

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:48.210
And so starting from a trip
that Kaki took to Cognac,

00:11:48.210 --> 00:11:52.340
Kaki composed the 200 beats
song to hundreds of the 200

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:53.660
years of the limited edition.

00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:56.810
And then I dissected and
analyzed every single movement

00:11:56.810 --> 00:11:59.450
that Kaki does with her
hands as she plays this song.

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:00.452
And this is--

00:12:00.452 --> 00:12:01.930
KAKI KING: Every
single movement.

00:12:01.930 --> 00:12:04.370
GIORGIA LUPI: It was
kind of laborious, Yeah.

00:12:04.370 --> 00:12:06.400
KAKI KING: Yeah, it was
incredibly laborious.

00:12:09.130 --> 00:12:12.880
Yeah, so normally when you
have music, you have notation.

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:14.380
With guitar, you
can have tablature,

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:15.910
which is a map of the
neck of the guitar,

00:12:15.910 --> 00:12:16.993
where to place your hands.

00:12:16.993 --> 00:12:20.740
But in this case, it was
if the left hand index

00:12:20.740 --> 00:12:24.580
finger swipes up
on this beat, that

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:28.210
is its own symbol, as
opposed to the middle finger

00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:30.190
of the right hand doing so.

00:12:30.190 --> 00:12:32.590
I am still--

00:12:32.590 --> 00:12:34.450
I mean, even after so
many collaborations,

00:12:34.450 --> 00:12:36.670
I'm still floored that
you went to the length

00:12:36.670 --> 00:12:38.581
that you did to
dissect what you did.

00:12:38.581 --> 00:12:40.830
And the cool thing about
it-- as you're going to see--

00:12:40.830 --> 00:12:42.540
it wraps around the box.

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:45.350
And it is a tribute to
the 200 years of VSOP.

00:12:45.350 --> 00:12:48.520
GIORGIA LUPI: Yeah, my work
tends to get pretty detailed.

00:12:48.520 --> 00:12:50.314
I tend to get very
obsessed with that.

00:12:50.314 --> 00:12:52.230
KAKI KING: Your brain
is built for it, though.

00:12:52.230 --> 00:12:53.050
GIORGIA LUPI: Yeah.

00:12:53.050 --> 00:12:55.341
Well, I mean, so this is the
idea of the whole process.

00:12:55.341 --> 00:12:57.340
And then visually,
I was taking cues

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:00.370
from Hennessy's visual legacy,
which is really done of all

00:13:00.370 --> 00:13:02.080
of these calligraphy types.

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:04.840
And I plotted all of that
into this visual score,

00:13:04.840 --> 00:13:08.620
where every vertical line is
one beat-- so again, 200 beats--

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:10.660
to create the visual
centerpiece of the branding

00:13:10.660 --> 00:13:11.750
on this special edition.

00:13:11.750 --> 00:13:14.452
And this is how it
looks like in the end.

00:13:14.452 --> 00:13:15.910
So again, every
symbol that you see

00:13:15.910 --> 00:13:17.470
is really the
representation of things

00:13:17.470 --> 00:13:18.720
that Kaki does with her hands.

00:13:18.720 --> 00:13:21.610
And I mean, I feel like-- and
we are starting to open up this

00:13:21.610 --> 00:13:23.620
into a more
conversational thing--

00:13:23.620 --> 00:13:27.190
I feel that the reason why
we decided to go this far

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:29.290
is that there's only
so much information

00:13:29.290 --> 00:13:32.020
that can be told through
a score or a tablature.

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:33.790
And especially in
Kaki's case-- and you've

00:13:33.790 --> 00:13:35.590
heard how she plays--
there is a lot that

00:13:35.590 --> 00:13:37.180
can be really transformed.

00:13:37.180 --> 00:13:39.910
KAKI KING: It's hard even
to transcribe what I do

00:13:39.910 --> 00:13:42.250
and to make it as
specific as possible.

00:13:42.250 --> 00:13:44.170
It's still very
difficult for people--

00:13:44.170 --> 00:13:47.700
without seeing me do it or
having it explained to them,

00:13:47.700 --> 00:13:50.410
it's hard for it
to just be placed

00:13:50.410 --> 00:13:53.620
on a traditional notation
in tablature score.

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:54.550
GIORGIA LUPI: Yeah.

00:13:54.550 --> 00:13:57.340
But then Kaki and I fell in
love with each other's work.

00:13:57.340 --> 00:14:00.160
And we decided to keep
exploring together.

00:14:00.160 --> 00:14:01.870
Early last year, we
guided an audience

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:05.260
of 2,000 people in
the Opera Theater

00:14:05.260 --> 00:14:09.520
in Cape Town on how to see music
exactly as we were describing,

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:11.950
based, again, on a laborious
representation of what

00:14:11.950 --> 00:14:14.830
Kaki does with her hands
on her guitar as she plays.

00:14:14.830 --> 00:14:17.830
And actually in this case, where
both the song and the visuals

00:14:17.830 --> 00:14:21.100
were informed by personal data
collection from our lives.

00:14:21.100 --> 00:14:23.560
As I did into your data,
we also did it together

00:14:23.560 --> 00:14:27.520
to compose a structure for
Kaki to interpret what we did

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:30.070
in our days and compose a song.

00:14:30.070 --> 00:14:32.110
And this is the
visualization of the song

00:14:32.110 --> 00:14:34.440
that she played live as
she guided the audience

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:36.520
to really understand
what every symbol means.

00:14:36.520 --> 00:14:39.700
And just really quickly,
in every section,

00:14:39.700 --> 00:14:42.370
the number of black lines
is the number of beats.

00:14:42.370 --> 00:14:45.640
And the symbol above represents
the song being played,

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:48.550
where the top of the
flower is Kaki's left hand

00:14:48.550 --> 00:14:50.649
and the bottom part
is her right hand.

00:14:50.649 --> 00:14:52.690
And the position of the
colors and the dimensions

00:14:52.690 --> 00:14:54.940
of the symbol represent
exactly the gestures

00:14:54.940 --> 00:14:56.380
that Kaki does with her hands.

00:14:56.380 --> 00:14:58.317
And it sounds like this.

00:14:58.317 --> 00:15:01.299
[GUITAR MUSIC]

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:47.370
But then, unfortunately,
something not pleasant

00:15:47.370 --> 00:15:48.330
happened.

00:15:48.330 --> 00:15:52.110
And I'd like Kaki
to describe it.

00:15:52.110 --> 00:15:55.034
KAKI KING: So Giorgia and I
had done these two projects

00:15:55.034 --> 00:15:57.450
together, which, you know,
when you work on a project that

00:15:57.450 --> 00:15:59.310
is as time-consuming
and laborious,

00:15:59.310 --> 00:16:02.730
and back and forth, as it is,
you get to know each other,

00:16:02.730 --> 00:16:06.310
even just doing one or two,
as was the case at this point.

00:16:06.310 --> 00:16:11.490
And so I had a trust in
Giorgia that I turned out

00:16:11.490 --> 00:16:13.140
would need, really.

00:16:13.140 --> 00:16:15.760
My daughter, who at the
time was almost three

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:18.265
this last year-- this is
her in her hospital bed.

00:16:18.265 --> 00:16:20.640
She was diagnosed with a very
strange autoimmune disorder

00:16:20.640 --> 00:16:22.122
called ITP.

00:16:22.122 --> 00:16:23.580
It's normally not
life-threatening.

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:29.340
But it causes your body to
attack its platelets, which is

00:16:29.340 --> 00:16:30.690
essential for blood clotting.

00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:32.970
So my daughter basically
woke up one morning

00:16:32.970 --> 00:16:34.291
and had blood in her mouth.

00:16:34.291 --> 00:16:35.790
She was just
spontaneously bleeding,

00:16:35.790 --> 00:16:38.100
and it was terrifying.

00:16:38.100 --> 00:16:42.990
This is her in the hospital
with her owl, her trusty owl.

00:16:42.990 --> 00:16:45.135
Her arm is wrapped up
because she's having an IV.

00:16:45.135 --> 00:16:47.010
She's actually having
a platelet transfusion.

00:16:47.010 --> 00:16:50.640
She had two of those, and it
was absolutely terrifying.

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:53.560
It's a strange disorder.

00:16:53.560 --> 00:16:58.470
It's very, very weird when you
are told that your daughter's

00:16:58.470 --> 00:16:59.690
body is attacking itself.

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:02.679
If it's something from the
outside, it's like, OK, look.

00:17:02.679 --> 00:17:04.470
We can fix this, we
can make sense of this.

00:17:04.470 --> 00:17:06.750
But that's what's
happening inside.

00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:10.020
And also, there's very few side
effects when children have it.

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:11.140
So she was fine.

00:17:11.140 --> 00:17:13.380
She didn't have
fever or fatigue.

00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:15.500
But you can show them
the next one, yes.

00:17:15.500 --> 00:17:17.190
This is what was
happening to her body.

00:17:17.190 --> 00:17:18.930
Spontaneously, these
types of bruises

00:17:18.930 --> 00:17:21.480
were coming up everywhere.

00:17:21.480 --> 00:17:24.300
My son had been born
just a few weeks earlier.

00:17:24.300 --> 00:17:27.810
So we had a new
baby and a daughter

00:17:27.810 --> 00:17:30.181
with a very strange illness.

00:17:30.181 --> 00:17:31.680
So the family was
kind of separated.

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:33.430
I stayed in the hospital
with my daughter.

00:17:33.430 --> 00:17:37.310
And I just watched these
bruises appear on her body.

00:17:37.310 --> 00:17:42.590
But a few weeks into the
process, she was sent home.

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:43.565
She had medications.

00:17:43.565 --> 00:17:45.690
We were told, you know,
don't let her hurt herself.

00:17:45.690 --> 00:17:46.680
Don't let her fall off the--

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:48.346
I mean, she's a very
rambunctious child.

00:17:48.346 --> 00:17:49.917
So that was hard.

00:17:49.917 --> 00:17:51.000
I started to collect data.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.970
Because I knew
that this was a way

00:17:54.970 --> 00:18:00.340
to keep track of what was
happening with her, but also,

00:18:00.340 --> 00:18:02.620
I think, that it really
became more about me.

00:18:02.620 --> 00:18:05.320
Because I was losing my--

00:18:05.320 --> 00:18:09.580
I was not parenting
well, I was not

00:18:09.580 --> 00:18:13.720
coping well, and collecting
data on my daughter,

00:18:13.720 --> 00:18:15.580
on her medications,
on her bruises,

00:18:15.580 --> 00:18:16.650
on all of these things.

00:18:16.650 --> 00:18:19.120
And then at the end
of my data collection

00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:22.600
was the annotations part,
with basically the information

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:23.890
I had about myself.

00:18:23.890 --> 00:18:25.150
And I recognized that.

00:18:25.150 --> 00:18:28.060
So we would go back to the
doctor, get her platelet count,

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:29.230
get her number.

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:31.990
And I would base my
life off of that number,

00:18:31.990 --> 00:18:34.210
whether I was happy
or sad, or able

00:18:34.210 --> 00:18:39.710
to deal with some other
issue or not, or I had to--

00:18:39.710 --> 00:18:44.260
and I connected my emotions
and my stability to this number

00:18:44.260 --> 00:18:46.360
that, for my daughter,
really wasn't--

00:18:46.360 --> 00:18:47.650
it wasn't affecting her.

00:18:47.650 --> 00:18:50.860
She was still happy,
and she was energetic.

00:18:50.860 --> 00:18:53.530
And she just happened to
have this thing that she was

00:18:53.530 --> 00:18:55.720
hopefully going to grow out of.

00:18:55.720 --> 00:18:58.420
So the data collection
we did really

00:18:58.420 --> 00:19:02.320
helped me disconnect
from what was happening

00:19:02.320 --> 00:19:04.989
to her medically versus what was
happening to her emotionally.

00:19:04.989 --> 00:19:05.780
GIORGIA LUPI: Yeah.

00:19:05.780 --> 00:19:07.910
So I mean, if you
think about it,

00:19:07.910 --> 00:19:09.520
ITP is a very visual disease.

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:11.170
And in this moment
of uncertainty,

00:19:11.170 --> 00:19:15.310
what Kaki was doing, and what I
was trying to support her with,

00:19:15.310 --> 00:19:18.650
is define a structure for how
to observe what was happening.

00:19:18.650 --> 00:19:22.600
And so she started
the daily observation

00:19:22.600 --> 00:19:25.120
of a mix of quantitative
and qualitative information,

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:27.010
really bringing together
the clinical inputs

00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:30.090
from Cooper's lab tests together
with much more soft data,

00:19:30.090 --> 00:19:33.400
if we want to think data-wise,
from Kaki's observation

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:34.330
and from her life.

00:19:34.330 --> 00:19:37.780
And we did so primarily to
channel stress and anxiety

00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:40.150
into a semblance of control.

00:19:40.150 --> 00:19:43.510
But also, as a step further
in our collaboration,

00:19:43.510 --> 00:19:45.760
we decided to share
this story, the story

00:19:45.760 --> 00:19:49.630
of the fourth month of data
collection, through data only.

00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:51.580
And as I was reading
Kaki's records,

00:19:51.580 --> 00:19:53.590
I was really
overwhelmed by feeling.

00:19:53.590 --> 00:19:55.630
And the things that
I asked myself,

00:19:55.630 --> 00:19:58.360
as a person who then worked
with data as a material

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:01.360
to build a narrative,
can that data

00:20:01.360 --> 00:20:03.990
visualization evoke also
empathy and activate,

00:20:03.990 --> 00:20:06.580
as in the people
who looks at that,

00:20:06.580 --> 00:20:09.940
also at an emotional level and
not only at a cognitive one?

00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:12.070
And can looking at
a data visualization

00:20:12.070 --> 00:20:16.740
make you feel part of a
story of a human life?

00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:18.490
So then I'll guide you
through the process

00:20:18.490 --> 00:20:19.364
of the visualization.

00:20:19.364 --> 00:20:21.280
And then we'll tell
you more about it.

00:20:21.280 --> 00:20:23.680
I structured this
fluid timeline,

00:20:23.680 --> 00:20:25.210
where each white element--

00:20:25.210 --> 00:20:26.440
we can call them petals--

00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:28.750
is a different day, for
a total of four months

00:20:28.750 --> 00:20:29.990
of data collection.

00:20:29.990 --> 00:20:32.590
And as Kaki was
anticipating, the time

00:20:32.590 --> 00:20:34.960
that is structured in
sections are the moments

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:36.550
in between the
readings, meaning when

00:20:36.550 --> 00:20:38.320
Cooper was admitted
to the hospital

00:20:38.320 --> 00:20:39.760
to have her blood checked.

00:20:39.760 --> 00:20:41.820
Because this moment
really paced their days.

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:43.360
And so the timeline
of the months

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:46.060
was not linear in their life.

00:20:46.060 --> 00:20:47.620
And every time
there is a lab test,

00:20:47.620 --> 00:20:49.090
we start a new group of petals.

00:20:49.090 --> 00:20:51.400
And the platelet counts
from the lab tests

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:53.080
are represented
by these red dots

00:20:53.080 --> 00:20:55.254
at the beginning of
each group of days.

00:20:55.254 --> 00:20:56.920
And we need to say
that the normal range

00:20:56.920 --> 00:21:00.850
for a platelet count
varies from 150 to 400.

00:21:00.850 --> 00:21:03.520
And so the numbers
of 1, 7, and 30

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:08.530
that you see in the beginning
are really frightening.

00:21:08.530 --> 00:21:10.870
And then I began to
incorporate Cooper's skin

00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:12.730
as was observed by Kaki.

00:21:12.730 --> 00:21:14.980
The intensity of the
bruises is represented

00:21:14.980 --> 00:21:16.900
by these purple and
green splotches.

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:18.770
Of course, the more
intense and present,

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:23.147
the more they were present
that day on Cooper's skin.

00:21:23.147 --> 00:21:24.480
KAKI KING: And sorry to jump in.

00:21:24.480 --> 00:21:27.830
But those were really
hard things to quantify.

00:21:27.830 --> 00:21:31.300
And I knew that, again,
my trust in Giorgia

00:21:31.300 --> 00:21:37.880
was that I could say, you
know, these bruises are bigger

00:21:37.880 --> 00:21:39.080
or they're more purple.

00:21:39.080 --> 00:21:40.160
What happens when
you have a bruise

00:21:40.160 --> 00:21:41.576
and you have ITP
is your platelets

00:21:41.576 --> 00:21:43.580
don't rush in to help
the clotting process.

00:21:43.580 --> 00:21:45.680
So you sort of bleed
into your bruise.

00:21:45.680 --> 00:21:48.230
And an old bruise
can even become new

00:21:48.230 --> 00:21:50.060
if your platelet count drops.

00:21:50.060 --> 00:21:51.560
The blood simply
starts to leak out.

00:21:54.459 --> 00:21:56.000
And there's also
these things-- and I

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.010
know you're about to speak
about them-- but petechiae.

00:21:58.010 --> 00:21:59.926
And they're basically
just burst blood vessels

00:21:59.926 --> 00:22:03.470
under the skin that can
also happen spontaneously.

00:22:03.470 --> 00:22:06.800
Normally, if you scrape yourself
and don't break the skin,

00:22:06.800 --> 00:22:09.440
you might get a few,
but they go away fast.

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:11.980
There would just be this
horrible rash on her neck,

00:22:11.980 --> 00:22:14.040
on her face.

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:16.790
So yeah, it was a very
visual disease, but one that

00:22:16.790 --> 00:22:20.180
was really hard to measure.

00:22:20.180 --> 00:22:23.330
And so I had to use descriptive
words, rather than numbers,

00:22:23.330 --> 00:22:23.830
at times.

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:24.621
GIORGIA LUPI: Yeah.

00:22:24.621 --> 00:22:26.750
And when I was reading
these, I was not, of course,

00:22:26.750 --> 00:22:29.005
interested in exact numbers
of bruises in petechiae,

00:22:29.005 --> 00:22:31.640
but about the four
month of data collection

00:22:31.640 --> 00:22:34.410
and the evolution of
all of this over time.

00:22:34.410 --> 00:22:38.030
And so I took my own ways to
measure the intensity based

00:22:38.030 --> 00:22:40.615
on the top, the day
that they were higher

00:22:40.615 --> 00:22:41.990
and the day that
they were lower.

00:22:41.990 --> 00:22:45.530
And I tried to use these
strokes and brushes that

00:22:45.530 --> 00:22:48.680
can resemble visually the
disease in a way that also

00:22:48.680 --> 00:22:50.965
helped us quantify the
data and really see

00:22:50.965 --> 00:22:53.090
the picture, or the big
picture, that you're seeing

00:22:53.090 --> 00:22:56.110
over a longer period of time.

00:22:56.110 --> 00:22:57.860
Well, by then, we added
details about when

00:22:57.860 --> 00:23:01.000
Cooper was taking medication--
steroids, specifically--

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:04.680
and they are these grape
shapes that affects the day.

00:23:04.680 --> 00:23:08.420
Also, Cooper had some incidents,
such as she fell at the park

00:23:08.420 --> 00:23:11.390
while playing or she got
bitten by a mosquito, that

00:23:11.390 --> 00:23:12.890
caused her skin to worsen.

00:23:12.890 --> 00:23:17.400
And we wanted to see how
that affected the skin,

00:23:17.400 --> 00:23:19.310
so we also included that.

00:23:19.310 --> 00:23:22.070
And you see how these fluid
timelines begin to take form

00:23:22.070 --> 00:23:24.390
and to visually tell the
story of these months.

00:23:24.390 --> 00:23:26.390
And again, as Kaki
was describing,

00:23:26.390 --> 00:23:28.130
besides medical
data, there's also

00:23:28.130 --> 00:23:31.400
what was going on in Kaki's
life and in her mind.

00:23:31.400 --> 00:23:32.225
She tours a lot.

00:23:32.225 --> 00:23:33.890
And she felt very
stressed when away

00:23:33.890 --> 00:23:35.804
from home in this
particular period of time.

00:23:35.804 --> 00:23:37.220
And the days that
she was gone are

00:23:37.220 --> 00:23:42.080
indicated with these black dots
on the days that she was gone.

00:23:42.080 --> 00:23:46.480
There also have been, luckily,
positive moments in these four

00:23:46.480 --> 00:23:49.310
months, such as a fun
birthday party for Cooper

00:23:49.310 --> 00:23:52.160
or her brother, or a
great Halloween night,

00:23:52.160 --> 00:23:55.040
that I represented as these
bright yellow spots that

00:23:55.040 --> 00:23:57.140
cheer up the visual, in a way.

00:23:57.140 --> 00:24:00.170
And lastly, Kaki also kept track
of her level of hope and fear

00:24:00.170 --> 00:24:03.290
for the day that she reported
on a scale from 1 to 10

00:24:03.290 --> 00:24:06.080
for both emotions, and
that here are visualized

00:24:06.080 --> 00:24:08.140
through the floating
lines framing the days,

00:24:08.140 --> 00:24:09.980
where the dark
lines are her fears

00:24:09.980 --> 00:24:11.750
and the orange
line are her hopes.

00:24:11.750 --> 00:24:15.750
And as she was describing,
this whole process

00:24:15.750 --> 00:24:18.020
is not only about
Cooper, but it's mostly

00:24:18.020 --> 00:24:20.900
about Kaki, and her
life, and their feelings.

00:24:20.900 --> 00:24:24.380
And all around, we had some
bits of Kaki's personal notes

00:24:24.380 --> 00:24:25.020
for the day.

00:24:25.020 --> 00:24:26.390
And this is the final artwork.

00:24:26.390 --> 00:24:29.210
And ultimately, these data
also became, of course,

00:24:29.210 --> 00:24:32.240
a piece of music that she
composed directly from the four

00:24:32.240 --> 00:24:33.399
months of data collection.

00:24:33.399 --> 00:24:35.190
And I don't know if
you want to explain it.

00:24:35.190 --> 00:24:36.410
But this is the score that--

00:24:36.410 --> 00:24:38.510
KAKI KING: This is
my score to help

00:24:38.510 --> 00:24:46.520
me analyze the data
that I had written down

00:24:46.520 --> 00:24:48.550
and to create a piece of music.

00:24:48.550 --> 00:24:49.890
So these are all the measures.

00:24:49.890 --> 00:24:54.940
So I believe we did each beat--
no, each measures is a day.

00:24:54.940 --> 00:24:57.760
GIORGIA LUPI: Yeah, and
the song is 120 measures,

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:01.100
covering the 248 and 20
days of data collection.

00:25:01.100 --> 00:25:02.900
And the timeline of
the song is exactly

00:25:02.900 --> 00:25:05.420
representing what was
happening in their life,

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:07.552
exactly, as the
data visualization.

00:25:07.552 --> 00:25:09.260
Yeah, there are elements
in the song that

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:12.570
reference the amount of
petechiae on Cooper's skin,

00:25:12.570 --> 00:25:13.830
Kaki's changing mood.

00:25:13.830 --> 00:25:16.820
And the main guitar
part is a musical map

00:25:16.820 --> 00:25:19.370
of the bruises on Cooper's skin.

00:25:19.370 --> 00:25:21.410
KAKI KING: This is
a really hard one.

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:22.610
It was really hard.

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:26.270
And even now, having some
distance, looking back,

00:25:26.270 --> 00:25:29.180
I'm like, whoa, this is a very--

00:25:29.180 --> 00:25:32.960
but again, I owe
this all to you.

