00:40:38.260 --> 00:40:40.390
by mistake pick
a font or a color

00:40:40.390 --> 00:40:42.770
that the other person
didn't like in the book,

00:40:42.770 --> 00:40:43.450
in the website.

00:40:43.450 --> 00:40:46.200
So you have no idea what a
collaboration that doesn't work

00:40:46.200 --> 00:40:47.510
looks like.

00:40:47.510 --> 00:40:49.810
But I'm really, really
excited about I'm still

00:40:49.810 --> 00:40:51.070
collaborating with Stefanie.

00:40:51.070 --> 00:40:54.100
But I guess what I'm saying
is that what you and I do

00:40:54.100 --> 00:40:55.930
is so different.

00:40:55.930 --> 00:40:57.460
For me, collaborating
with you is

00:40:57.460 --> 00:41:00.910
having a source of data,
a source of inspiration,

00:41:00.910 --> 00:41:03.760
a source of really
things that are not

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:05.380
even comparable to my work.

00:41:05.380 --> 00:41:08.720
This is really a fool
to my work in a way.

00:41:08.720 --> 00:41:12.370
And I also believe that
our personalities--

00:41:12.370 --> 00:41:14.920
we really also joke about that.

00:41:14.920 --> 00:41:17.260
I send you pictures of
my perfectly organized

00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:19.130
and color-coded drawers
and folded things.

00:41:19.130 --> 00:41:22.210
KAKI KING: We do
have that in common.

00:41:22.210 --> 00:41:24.670
I have two children,
and I have a wife

00:41:24.670 --> 00:41:28.240
that works in set design, so
our house is just whatever.

00:41:28.240 --> 00:41:29.465
I mean, it's a disaster.

00:41:29.465 --> 00:41:31.090
GIORGIA LUPI: When
you need to breathe,

00:41:31.090 --> 00:41:31.780
I can send you
pictures of my house.

00:41:31.780 --> 00:41:33.840
KAKI KING: And when I need
to breathe, I ask Georgia,

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:36.010
can you just send me a
picture of your pens, just

00:41:36.010 --> 00:41:38.400
your organized pens?

00:41:38.400 --> 00:41:40.180
And I get these
beautiful photos.

00:41:40.180 --> 00:41:41.100
And I get so calm.

00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:42.280
And then I threaten her.

00:41:42.280 --> 00:41:45.890
I'm like, I'm going to send you
a photo of my medicine cabinet.

00:41:45.890 --> 00:41:48.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:51.420
So yeah, we do like clean
and organized things.

00:41:51.420 --> 00:41:54.010
We do have that in
common, for sure.

00:41:54.010 --> 00:41:56.850
And I think that ultimately,
I think we like our lives

00:41:56.850 --> 00:41:59.040
to be clean and
organized and our work

00:41:59.040 --> 00:42:01.380
to be powerful in that way.

00:42:01.380 --> 00:42:02.340
So no.

00:42:02.340 --> 00:42:05.290
No giant fights yet.

00:42:05.290 --> 00:42:10.800
But definitely, certainly
different personalities,

00:42:10.800 --> 00:42:14.370
but probably that have
arisen from the work

00:42:14.370 --> 00:42:16.480
that we've been in for so long.

00:42:16.480 --> 00:42:20.210
And I think my music and touring
has shaped who I am, for sure.

00:42:20.210 --> 00:42:21.210
GIORGIA LUPI: Of course.

00:42:21.210 --> 00:42:25.575
I mean, and I, on my hand-- and
then we'll change the subject--

00:42:25.575 --> 00:42:27.410
but I work with clients.

00:42:27.410 --> 00:42:29.190
Every time, I need
to be organized

00:42:29.190 --> 00:42:31.394
and precise with emails,
with deadlines, with stuff.

00:42:31.394 --> 00:42:33.060
I mean, it's really
different, probably,

00:42:33.060 --> 00:42:34.726
to be a musician, and
touring the world,

00:42:34.726 --> 00:42:36.700
and to run a company,
and working with data.

00:42:36.700 --> 00:42:40.870
So it's kind of, really, the
opposite end of the spectrum.

00:42:40.870 --> 00:42:43.382
But still I feel, again,
we meet in the middle.

00:42:43.382 --> 00:42:45.340
SPEAKER 1: Well, on the
topic of organization--

00:42:45.340 --> 00:42:48.800
and I think we do have a couple
more minutes for questions.

00:42:48.800 --> 00:42:50.790
If anybody else, please
make your way to a mic.

00:42:50.790 --> 00:42:53.070
On the topic of
the organization,

00:42:53.070 --> 00:42:56.940
it makes me curious about
with the flowers project.

00:42:56.940 --> 00:43:00.990
When you saw that
visually represented,

00:43:00.990 --> 00:43:05.824
how did you process
that's what you're doing?

00:43:05.824 --> 00:43:07.740
Because you talk about
not really fussing over

00:43:07.740 --> 00:43:08.910
the details.

00:43:08.910 --> 00:43:11.086
When you see it laid
out and so detailed of,

00:43:11.086 --> 00:43:12.960
like, yeah, that's your
finger moving, that's

00:43:12.960 --> 00:43:14.790
this other finger and this.

00:43:14.790 --> 00:43:16.800
How did that impact you?

00:43:16.800 --> 00:43:21.580
KAKI KING: I think it
is such an exciting--

00:43:26.070 --> 00:43:29.260
I feel honored that what
I do is interesting enough

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:32.300
to know the person, not just
to learn it on the guitar,

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:34.910
or not just to be
curious about what it is.

00:43:34.910 --> 00:43:38.440
But to be able to take
the time to work out

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:44.470
exactly what it is that
each finger on each hand

00:43:44.470 --> 00:43:47.170
is precisely doing.

00:43:47.170 --> 00:43:51.010
And the result is beautiful.

00:43:51.010 --> 00:43:53.080
For me, when I look
at Giorgia's work,

00:43:53.080 --> 00:43:55.360
it's about the
result. Again, I'm not

00:43:55.360 --> 00:43:56.620
the most detailed person.

00:43:56.620 --> 00:43:58.622
So you can read
the legend, you can

00:43:58.622 --> 00:43:59.830
see exactly what's happening.

00:43:59.830 --> 00:44:00.970
You can decipher it all.

00:44:00.970 --> 00:44:03.490
It's all built on something
with this-- you know,

00:44:03.490 --> 00:44:06.290
it all exists in the real world.

00:44:06.290 --> 00:44:12.160
But that is less
important to me than what

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:15.040
has come out of it, which
is this glorious picture

00:44:15.040 --> 00:44:18.340
of these beautiful, strange
flowers that have opened up.

00:44:18.340 --> 00:44:22.030
So it's hard for me to
believe that that's my music,

00:44:22.030 --> 00:44:24.040
that literally,
that is my music.

00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:26.170
That is Giorgia's
interpretation of,

00:44:26.170 --> 00:44:27.940
but that it's every
single thing that I do

00:44:27.940 --> 00:44:30.260
is contained in that
visual representation.

00:44:30.260 --> 00:44:31.570
So I think it's just this--

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:32.500
it's awe.

00:44:32.500 --> 00:44:35.980
I'm just in awe of
both my sheer luck

00:44:35.980 --> 00:44:39.520
that I get to work with
someone that cares enough.

00:44:39.520 --> 00:44:41.302
that It resonates.

00:44:41.302 --> 00:44:43.510
Every time you go to a
conference and you present it,

00:44:43.510 --> 00:44:44.970
you're like, Kaki,
people loved it.

00:44:44.970 --> 00:44:46.270
It was great.

00:44:46.270 --> 00:44:47.670
GIORGIA LUPI: That's so true.

00:44:47.670 --> 00:44:50.000
KAKI KING: Yeah.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.540
And not being a person
that has any origin,

00:44:52.540 --> 00:44:58.630
individual or tech world,
at all to be invited in

00:44:58.630 --> 00:45:02.710
and to be having my music
expressed in this way is just--

00:45:02.710 --> 00:45:04.000
I'm floored, I'm honored.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:05.187
And it's just very special.

00:45:05.187 --> 00:45:07.270
GIORGIA LUPI: But you
started to work with visuals

00:45:07.270 --> 00:45:08.300
even before meeting me.

00:45:08.300 --> 00:45:10.090
So I guess that you
were already drawn

00:45:10.090 --> 00:45:15.070
into making your music not
only listenable, but also--

00:45:15.070 --> 00:45:16.270
KAKI KING: It's true.

00:45:16.270 --> 00:45:18.880
I had been starting
to work with visuals.

00:45:18.880 --> 00:45:25.262
But the connection was
very soft, and not this--

00:45:25.262 --> 00:45:26.470
GIORGIA LUPI: Yeah, not data.

00:45:26.470 --> 00:45:27.850
KAKI KING: Not
data driven, yeah.

00:45:27.850 --> 00:45:29.225
SPEAKER 1: Well,
and I think it's

00:45:29.225 --> 00:45:33.010
a great nexus of a lot of
different wants, and needs,

00:45:33.010 --> 00:45:36.610
and weird triangulation
way, in that musicians

00:45:36.610 --> 00:45:38.770
forever have sought
to make music

00:45:38.770 --> 00:45:40.750
videos to have a visualization.

00:45:40.750 --> 00:45:42.890
And people in the big
data world are like, well,

00:45:42.890 --> 00:45:45.650
if it's just a bunch of
numbers, it's very dry.

00:45:45.650 --> 00:45:48.310
So how do you make that
visually interesting,

00:45:48.310 --> 00:45:51.790
or just interesting beyond
people who really like numbers?

00:45:51.790 --> 00:45:55.780
And this seems to be a
great triad nexus of music

00:45:55.780 --> 00:45:58.090
meets visual meets data.

00:45:58.090 --> 00:46:01.380
And it's presented in a truly
awesome and awe-inspiring way.

00:46:01.380 --> 00:46:03.489
So thank you very much, both.

00:46:03.489 --> 00:46:04.780
We do have a couple of minutes.

00:46:04.780 --> 00:46:07.724
Would you mind gracing
us with another song?

00:46:07.724 --> 00:46:09.140
Oh, did you have
another question?

00:46:09.140 --> 00:46:09.848
Yeah, absolutely.

00:46:09.848 --> 00:46:12.860
AUDIENCE: I'd prefer hearing
another song, actually.

00:46:12.860 --> 00:46:14.526
SPEAKER 1: I think
we got time for both.

00:46:14.526 --> 00:46:15.550
Please.

00:46:15.550 --> 00:46:17.904
AUDIENCE: First of all, thank
you both for being here.

00:46:17.904 --> 00:46:20.320
Kaki, I was just wondering if
you could share a little bit

00:46:20.320 --> 00:46:25.390
about how you normally approach
writing songs from scratch,

00:46:25.390 --> 00:46:31.060
and then how it's different
to approach this song,

00:46:31.060 --> 00:46:33.310
where you have these parameters
set out for you, where

00:46:33.310 --> 00:46:38.074
if this data point represents
a percussion to hit here,

00:46:38.074 --> 00:46:40.240
you sort of have to follow
that through for the rest

00:46:40.240 --> 00:46:41.320
of the song.

00:46:41.320 --> 00:46:43.460
KAKI KING: So when I
write a song from scratch,

00:46:43.460 --> 00:46:46.420
I have total freedom.

00:46:46.420 --> 00:46:50.230
Tempos, moods,
tunings, whatever--

00:46:50.230 --> 00:46:54.430
I have no parameters, which
can be its own challenge.

00:46:54.430 --> 00:47:00.920
With this tune, like I said,
sort of cramming data in--

00:47:00.920 --> 00:47:02.080
I want to say cramming.

00:47:02.080 --> 00:47:05.380
But when I get frustrated,
that's how I feel.

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:08.470
Because I feel like I'm not
servicing the data in the way

00:47:08.470 --> 00:47:10.210
it should be.

00:47:10.210 --> 00:47:15.980
And then there's certain musical
elements that just need to be--

00:47:15.980 --> 00:47:16.780
there's a timeline.

00:47:16.780 --> 00:47:18.235
There should be a beat.

00:47:18.235 --> 00:47:20.800
There has to be an
opening and closing point.

00:47:20.800 --> 00:47:23.290
So we did four months
of data because that

00:47:23.290 --> 00:47:25.360
would fit into a
three minute song

00:47:25.360 --> 00:47:31.340
with each measure being
three beats and 120 measures.

00:47:31.340 --> 00:47:36.370
But basically, we had to cap
it to allow it to make sense

00:47:36.370 --> 00:47:38.530
visually and musically.

00:47:38.530 --> 00:47:42.820
And so for instance, there is a
part where my mood would shift,

00:47:42.820 --> 00:47:45.040
and the piano sound
would go from a major

00:47:45.040 --> 00:47:47.770
to a minor, or the
underlying synthesizer sound.

00:47:47.770 --> 00:47:49.600
And I wasn't exactly
happy with it

00:47:49.600 --> 00:47:52.240
because occasionally,
it wouldn't

00:47:52.240 --> 00:47:54.040
happen in a four bar phrase.

00:47:54.040 --> 00:47:57.310
It would sort of happen in
a bar five or a bar seven.

00:47:57.310 --> 00:48:00.820
And even though I'm hip to
that, it wasn't always working.

00:48:00.820 --> 00:48:06.100
So without shifting anything,
I nudged a little bit.

00:48:06.100 --> 00:48:08.770
I sort of did that.

00:48:08.770 --> 00:48:11.570
So trying to retain all of
the integrity of the data

00:48:11.570 --> 00:48:13.810
and retaining the
integrity of music

00:48:13.810 --> 00:48:16.010
is actually hugely challenging.

00:48:16.010 --> 00:48:18.010
And that's something that
I think that I'm still

00:48:18.010 --> 00:48:19.559
figuring out the process of.

00:48:19.559 --> 00:48:21.100
GIORGIA LUPI: If I
can add one thing.

00:48:21.100 --> 00:48:23.500
Following you from afar as
you were composing the music--

00:48:23.500 --> 00:48:25.770
like, not from afar,
but from the outside--

00:48:25.770 --> 00:48:28.150
is not that you
decided what notes

00:48:28.150 --> 00:48:29.430
to play based on the data.

00:48:29.430 --> 00:48:32.260
But you had some melodies in
mind, or melodies that like,

00:48:32.260 --> 00:48:35.340
let's say,
combinations of sounds

00:48:35.340 --> 00:48:37.900
that then would integrate
the timelines and the data

00:48:37.900 --> 00:48:38.440
collection.

00:48:38.440 --> 00:48:43.130
So it was not really a direct
translation of data a note,

00:48:43.130 --> 00:48:44.260
G minor or something.

00:48:44.260 --> 00:48:45.790
But it was more
like, OK, following

00:48:45.790 --> 00:48:48.370
some structures, knowing
that there are some sections,

00:48:48.370 --> 00:48:52.300
and moments that needed to
be represented with a sound

00:48:52.300 --> 00:48:55.610
to really pay the truth
to the data collection.

00:48:55.610 --> 00:48:57.562
But there were
moments when I feel

00:48:57.562 --> 00:48:59.020
it's not that you
were improvising,

00:48:59.020 --> 00:49:04.990
but that you took a fair amount
of freedom in little phrases

00:49:04.990 --> 00:49:07.840
to express also things that
were really personal for you,

00:49:07.840 --> 00:49:09.000
like your changes of mood.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:10.570
So I guess I'm saying
it's not really

00:49:10.570 --> 00:49:14.110
always a direct translation,
but it's more like data that

00:49:14.110 --> 00:49:15.670
informs the music composition.

00:49:15.670 --> 00:49:17.410
Whereas with data
visualization, probably

00:49:17.410 --> 00:49:18.890
also because it's
more formalized

00:49:18.890 --> 00:49:21.950
and because people need
to understand and see--

00:49:21.950 --> 00:49:24.640
well, data visualization--
it is a direct translation

00:49:24.640 --> 00:49:26.110
of the data points.

00:49:26.110 --> 00:49:28.750
KAKI KING: Well, but also what
you do and with your focus

00:49:28.750 --> 00:49:32.980
on data humanism, it
allows me to look at data

00:49:32.980 --> 00:49:35.980
and say, I have a feeling now.

00:49:35.980 --> 00:49:38.152
So much of what you do--

00:49:38.152 --> 00:49:39.610
with your data,
with other things--

00:49:39.610 --> 00:49:43.840
has so much personal
emotion built into it.

00:49:43.840 --> 00:49:45.520
And music is the
language of emotion,

00:49:45.520 --> 00:49:47.290
especially instrumental
music, which

00:49:47.290 --> 00:49:49.030
is a language I'm
very familiar with.

00:49:49.030 --> 00:49:53.830
So it's almost like, is it more
important for this precise note

00:49:53.830 --> 00:49:56.980
to land on this exact
measure to represent

00:49:56.980 --> 00:49:58.540
when we were in the hospital?

00:49:58.540 --> 00:50:01.180
Or is it more important
to you to feel that?

00:50:01.180 --> 00:50:02.890
And I think that
the data humanism

00:50:02.890 --> 00:50:05.920
aspect of Giorgia's
work and music

00:50:05.920 --> 00:50:08.590
allows that
connection to be made,

00:50:08.590 --> 00:50:12.190
allows that freedom to
take a tiny bit of liberty,

00:50:12.190 --> 00:50:16.025
but still more effectively
getting the point across.

00:50:16.025 --> 00:50:16.900
SPEAKER 1: Excellent.

00:50:16.900 --> 00:50:18.230
Thank you.

00:50:18.230 --> 00:50:20.990
Again, just absolutely
astounding work.

00:50:20.990 --> 00:50:22.410
It's really beautiful.

00:50:22.410 --> 00:50:24.992
It's really sonically
amazing and astounding.

00:50:24.992 --> 00:50:26.450
And you both have
created something

00:50:26.450 --> 00:50:30.740
amazing that I think people
in the world can grow from,

00:50:30.740 --> 00:50:31.500
just watching.

00:50:31.500 --> 00:50:34.460
And hopefully, it
does have that impact.

00:50:34.460 --> 00:50:35.840
We look forward to what is next.

00:50:35.840 --> 00:50:39.500
Are you able to tell us anything
about this art and music baby?

00:50:42.860 --> 00:50:45.830
KAKI KING: Because of
the foray into performing

00:50:45.830 --> 00:50:48.980
arts and theatrical
work that's still

00:50:48.980 --> 00:50:51.320
based all around me
playing the guitar--

00:50:51.320 --> 00:50:54.440
but I have a lot more
creative freedom and license--

00:50:54.440 --> 00:50:56.450
and because of my
work with Giorgia,

00:50:56.450 --> 00:50:59.870
there are arts organizations out
there who are basically saying,

00:50:59.870 --> 00:51:04.490
we are inviting you to create
a work that incorporates what

00:51:04.490 --> 00:51:09.890
I do, what Giorgia does,
and tells more of a story

00:51:09.890 --> 00:51:10.580
through data.

00:51:10.580 --> 00:51:14.750
Not just data visualization,
but to kind of address

00:51:14.750 --> 00:51:19.400
all of what does that word do to
your mind and to talk about it.

00:51:19.400 --> 00:51:21.170
And Giorgia has been--

00:51:21.170 --> 00:51:31.060
I've sort of signified her as
my muse, and my consultant,

00:51:31.060 --> 00:51:32.570
and as well as
someone that's going

00:51:32.570 --> 00:51:35.000
to do a lot of visual
work for the show,

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:37.970
both in the things that
you've already seen

00:51:37.970 --> 00:51:40.405
and hopefully, some ways
that we haven't tried yet.

00:51:40.405 --> 00:51:41.780
GIORGIA LUPI:
Yeah. so it will be

00:51:41.780 --> 00:51:44.150
hopefully a full show together.

00:51:44.150 --> 00:51:45.620
Like with Kaki,
of course, that's

00:51:45.620 --> 00:51:47.840
going to be the person
playing in 2019.

00:51:47.840 --> 00:51:49.280
For me, it's also
real interesting

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:52.220
to take this idea
of data humanism

00:51:52.220 --> 00:51:55.160
and bring it outside the data
community or the visualization

00:51:55.160 --> 00:51:57.370
community, and try
to tell a story

00:51:57.370 --> 00:51:59.960
